BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-08T101551.202.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260421T092351Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Rustam Vania\n\nAt the top of the high-altitude Himalayan ranges lives the snow leopard\, elusive and solitary\, known as the ghost of the mountains. To protect it is to protect the fragile world it moves through. \n\nThis illustrated talk and interactive workshop takes you into that world\, tracing the delicate balance between human livelihoods\, conservation\, and the restoration of Himalayan ecosystems.\n\n&nbsp\;\n\nPlease note the interactive workshop has a few slots and requires registration. The illustrated talk\, open for all\, is from 7:00 PM to 8:30 PM.
DTEND:20260505T150000Z
DTSTART:20260505T123000Z
SUMMARY:The Ghosts of Conservation - Political Ecology of High Altitude Himalayan Landscapes
UID:1248@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/the-ghosts-of-conservation-political-ecology-of-high-altitude-himalayan-landscapes/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-16T150248.742.png
CATEGORIES:Panel Discussion,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260421T062257Z
DESCRIPTION:Food possesses the unique ability to unite communities while simultaneously perpetuating the exclusion of marginalised voices. A critical examination of the politics embedded in our food archives reveals the enduring influence of caste and colonial legacies.\n\nWhat factors determine the foods we come to know and consume? Join us for an intimate panel discussion with Vinay Kumar\, Sumaiya Mustafa and Rajyashri Goody\, moderated by Divya Kandukuri\, as they interrogate how social hierarchies\, particularly caste\, have sculpted Indian culinary narratives. Whose recipes are enshrined in history books as exemplars of 'authentic' Indian cuisine\, and whose remain overlooked? How do these dynamics manifest in the power of naming—whether plants\, recipes\, or adaptations for Western appeal?\n\nUltimately\, how might food serve as a transformative force to celebrate identity\, belonging\, and community?\n\nIn Part 1 of this panel series\, we bring together artists\, researchers\, and professors who examine food politics through the lens of caste. Part II explores the topic with a focus on food systems.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP's ongoing exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260425T130000Z
DTSTART:20260425T113000Z
SUMMARY:Archiving Food\, Archiving Power
UID:1257@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/archiving-food-archiving-power/
END:VEVENT
