BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-17T102803.522.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260421T062749Z
DESCRIPTION:Did you know that India began drinking coffee much before Europe? Yet we recognise the beverage as a colonial import\, even in households where grandmothers brewed the beverage in brass filters. Coffee’s trade and cultivation in England’s colonies corresponds in stages with the building of its empire\, facilitating novel interactions between people\, plants and microbes\, radically reshaping ethnobotanical and cultural boundaries.\n\nJoin us for a discussion around the fascinating story of coffee\, paired with a specially curated tasting menu of some of the finest Coffea canephora around.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260426T103000Z
DTSTART:20260426T090000Z
SUMMARY:Brewing across Time
UID:1254@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/brewing-across-time/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-22T104009.698.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260422T140824Z
DESCRIPTION:What does vulnerability look like? What does care feel like?\nThese are the questions that artist Afra Eisma leaves us with in warrior garments.\n\nJoin us for a three-part series of reflective feminist reading sessions\, developed in collaboration with Zubaan and  facilitated by Laxmi Murthy. Together\, we will explore gender-based violence—its lived realities\, and the possibilities of resistance\, solidarity\, and healing. Through stories\, essays\, and personal reflections\, you are invited to engage with the exhibition at your own pace\, in a space that encourages listening\, sharing\, and care.\n\nNote:\n\n-This is the first session in a three-part series presented alongside Warrior Garments. Each session is self-contained\, but we encourage participants to attend all three.\n\n-The upcoming sessions will take place on May 30 and June 21\, 2026.\n\n-Reading materials for each will be shared after registration.\n\nTrigger Warning: The sessions may include discussions on sexual violence.
DTEND:20260502T073000Z
DTSTART:20260502T053000Z
SUMMARY:Holding Space: Feminist Reading Circle
UID:1260@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/holding-space-feminist-reading-circle/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-13T095257.843.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260421T062443Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an immersive guided walk through the Ethno-Medicinal Garden at the University of Trans-Disciplinary Health Sciences and Technology.\n\nEncounter India's medicinal flora sensorially\, from familiar healing herbs to rare\, traded\, and endangered species that have sustained generations. Post the walk\, we will visit the university herbarium\, one of India’s most distinguished repositories dedicated to medicinal plants documented from across the country's diverse bio-geographical zones.\n\nOpen to students\, environmentalists\, artists and curious minds alike\, this walk is an invitation to slow down\, reconnect with nature's roots\, and reflect on the heritage of healing.\n\nPlease note: Transportation for the walk will be organised from MAP on 25th April at 9 am.\n\nConversations continue at the Herbarium Workshop at MAP on Sunday\, 26\, April.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260425T060000Z
DTSTART:20260425T043000Z
SUMMARY:Ethno-Medicinal Garden Walk
UID:1251@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/ethno-medicinal-garden-walk/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-08T095613.041.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260424T070155Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credit: A still from the video "Skin of Things 2025” by Asmita Sarkar\n\nMetaphors are more than ornaments of language. They shape our thoughts and help us find meaning and beauty\, by bringing into being new ways of seeing and articulating experience. The point of departure for this workshop is a few art-science explorations by artist and researcher Asmita Sarkar\, who has worked with sleep researchers at NCBS\, Bangalore. The exploration of circadian\, diurnal\, and circannual rhythms helps create metaphors that connect the molecular to the cosmic levels\, illustrating how various climate events influence human and non-human bodies. \n\nWorkshop participants will create their own climate change metaphors. Thus\, creating meaning out of different facets of a messy\, nebulous problem\, which apparently has no simple resolution.
DTEND:20260425T070000Z
DTSTART:20260425T050000Z
SUMMARY:Climate Metaphors
UID:1247@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/climate-metaphors/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-22T092946.933.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260422T044230Z
DESCRIPTION:A session that moves from gallery to garden.\nBegin with a guided walkthrough of Paper Gardens \, before stepping into the Living Botanical installation with its gardener\, Kush Sethi. Drawing connections between the artworks and the plants around you\, Kush will guide you through observing species\, forms\, compositions\, and the quiet details of plant anatomy.\nThe session then transitions into a hands-on gardening workshop\, slow-paced and unhurried\, where you will practise the art of potting and composing. A gentle introduction to becoming a plant parent.\nYour completed piece is yours to take home.
DTEND:20260509T103000Z
DTSTART:20260509T090000Z
SUMMARY:Plant Parenting 101
UID:1259@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/plant-parenting-101/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-16T141037.201.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260421T062539Z
DESCRIPTION:Following the ethno-medicinal garden walk and visit to the university herbarium\, this programme extends into a herbarium workshop.\n\nHere\, participants draw from their learnings from the repository and create their own herbariums to take home. Alongside learning traditional taxonomical principles for plant identification and nomenclature\, we archive these plants as living - through the names and ways we know to use them\, thereby building layered\, evolving understandings of  the plant world. \n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260426T080000Z
DTSTART:20260426T053000Z
SUMMARY:Herbarium Workshop
UID:1256@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/herbarium-workshop/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/nature-art-workshop-iisc-2024-scaled-e1775708092836.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260416T053429Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Dr Sambita Modak\n\nThrough this workshop\, we will connect the audience to the impacts of climate change on ecosystems and how these impacts affect the series of socio-economic linkages around us. The session will focus on three key lenses: biodiversity\, food and water systems\, and social fabric\, connecting these through storytelling and data visualisation. \n\nThrough art explorations\, we will examine themes such as climate grief\, climate injustice\, and the interconnection between them and ecosystems.
DTEND:20260509T140000Z
DTSTART:20260509T103000Z
SUMMARY:Climate Canvases
UID:1249@map-india.org
